# QLoRA Fine-Tuning of TinyLlama for News Summarization (CNN/DailyMail)
# Overview
This project implements efficient fine-tuning of a large language model (LLM) using QLoRA (Quantized Low-Rank Adaptation). The goal is to adapt the lightweight model TinyLlama-1.1B-Chat for the task of abstractive news summarization using the CNN/DailyMail dataset.
The model is trained to generate concise and meaningful summaries (highlights) from full news articles while maintaining computational efficiency.
________________________________________
Objective
The main objectives of this project are:
•	Fine-tune a pre-trained LLM for news summarization
•	Apply Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT) using LoRA
•	Reduce memory and compute requirements using 4-bit quantization
•	Evaluate generated summaries using ROUGE metrics
•	Demonstrate efficient adaptation of LLMs on limited resources
________________________________________
Dataset
•	Dataset: CNN/DailyMail (version 3.0.0)
•	Source: Hugging Face Datasets
•	Task: Abstractive summarization
Data Structure:
•	Input: Full news article
•	Target: Human-written summary (highlights)
A small subset (1% of the training set) was used for experimentation due to computational constraints.
________________________________________
Model Architecture
Base Model
•	TinyLlama/TinyLlama-1.1B-Chat-v1.0
•	Lightweight causal language model designed for instruction-based tasks
________________________________________
Efficient Training Strategy
1. Quantization (QLoRA Setup)
To reduce memory usage and enable efficient training:
•	4-bit quantization using NF4 format
•	Mixed precision (FP16)
•	Device mapping: automatic GPU allocation
________________________________________
2. LoRA Fine-Tuning
Only a small subset of parameters was trained using LoRA adapters:
•	Rank (r): 8
•	Alpha: 32
•	Dropout: 0.05
•	Target modules: q_proj, v_proj
•	Task type: Causal Language Modeling
📌 Only ~0.1% of total parameters were trainable.
________________________________________
Data Preprocessing
Each sample was transformed into a supervised learning format:
Summarize the following news article:
{article}
Summary:
Labeling Strategy:
•	The input (prompt + summary) is tokenized
•	Loss is computed only on the summary portion
•	Prompt tokens are masked using -100 to avoid influencing training loss
________________________________________
Training Configuration
•	Framework: Hugging Face Trainer API
•	Batch size: 1
•	Gradient accumulation: 4
•	Learning rate: 2e-4
•	Epochs: 1
•	Precision: FP16
•	Optimization: QLoRA + LoRA adapters
________________________________________
Evaluation
The model is evaluated using the ROUGE metric, which measures overlap between generated and reference summaries.
Metrics:
•	ROUGE-1
•	ROUGE-2
•	ROUGE-L
Evaluation Process:
•	Generate summaries for test articles
•	Compare model outputs with ground-truth highlights
•	Compute ROUGE scores using evaluate library
________________________________________
Results & Observations
•	The model successfully generates coherent and relevant summaries
•	QLoRA significantly reduces training cost while maintaining performance
•	Generated outputs capture key information from news articles
•	ROUGE scores indicate reasonable performance given limited training data
________________________________________
Key Contributions
•	Implemented a full LLM fine-tuning pipeline using QLoRA
•	Demonstrated efficient training on limited GPU resources
•	Applied PEFT techniques for large-scale model adaptation
•	Built an end-to-end summarization system using TinyLlama
________________________________________
Technologies Used
•	Python
•	PyTorch
•	Hugging Face Transformers
•	PEFT (LoRA / QLoRA)
•	BitsAndBytes
•	Datasets
•	Evaluate (ROUGE)
________________________________________
Conclusion
This project demonstrates how large language models can be efficiently fine-tuned using QLoRA for real-world NLP tasks such as news summarization. It highlights the effectiveness of parameter-efficient methods in reducing computational cost while maintaining strong generative performance.
